<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-09-13T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-09-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="652" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d652">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Adee</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Powell</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-09-13"><hi rend="italic">September 13,
                                    1902</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 541.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            telegram of the 11th instant, and confirm my telegram of the same date
                            in reply.</p>
                        <p>The implied assumption expressed in your telegram that the Provisional
                            Government acted through its agencies at Gonaives in permitting the
                            entry of French and German vessels, is unsound, because that port and
                            its approaches are held by adverse forces.</p>
                        <p>The argument is therefore illogical as well as irrelevant.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Alvey A. Adee</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>